We need to re-imagine the shape step as below:

The user needs 2 lists, work and personal. the work part is priority top down, Personal tasks are bottom up. User can drag items between the two lists and drag to prioritize. 

Each day should have a daily calendar showing appointments (timeline) and a list. This begs the question each day, I have the list of appoints on my timeline, where do I slot in these work and personal tasks. 

Start with appoint ments > then work > then personal

Then each task gets a unique id. This does not corespond to anything with priority or whatever, this is just a way to index tasks. The user may or may not have to see the unique ID, the software can handle that. This is the W1, w2 codes etc. The user shouldnt enter these, we should generate them for each code. (this is really a hold over from a paper based system as the code will do this for us, but we do need to be aware of the concept. )

The pile isnt a storage location, its an action. Items are entered into the pile, and then you go to step to Shape. this is where we will take each item in the pile and run them through the 5 filters. We can use 5 direction arrows to indicate the 5 filters. we can play with that later. 

Filters dont prioritize when the action should be done, the determine what kind of action (or lack of action) needs to be done. Almost a pre-priozation step. Delegate step could set an auto follow up with who you dellegated to. 

The next step is "when will I do each task?" This step should see the user through answering that question. 

One major insight here is PLAN ALL THE ITEMS IN THE LIST BEFORE YOU START WORKING THEM, even if theres a simple task you can do quickly. You sould have every item assigned before you start your day. 

